C = \frac{\epsilon_0 A}{d - t \left( 1 - \frac{1}{K} \right)}
For Glass, Mica and Ebonite, K is a finite number, so \left( 1 - \frac{1}{K} \right) is less than 1.
For Copper (a metal/conductor), the dielectric constant K \to \infty.
C_{copper} = \frac{\epsilon_0 A}{d - t (1 - 0)} = \frac{\epsilon_0 A}{d - t}
Since, the denominator (d - t) is the smallest possible value compared to the insulators, the capacitance C is maximum for the copper sheet.
